Title: A Christmas Carol
Credit: Screenplay adaptation of
Author: Charles Dickens's novella (1843, public domain)
Draft date: 7/18/2026

====

FADE IN:

INT. SCROOGE & MARLEY'S COUNTING-HOUSE - DAY

A cramped, cold office. EBENEZER SCROOGE (60s, pinched, sharp-eyed) sits at a desk stacked with ledgers. Through a small window, his clerk, BOB CRATCHIT, huddles over a single candle, breath visible in the cold.

SCROOGE
(not looking up)
Put another lump of coal on that fire and you'll be looking for new employment, Mr. Cratchit.

BOB CRATCHIT
(meekly)
Yes, sir.

Scrooge's nephew FRED bursts in, cheeks red from the cold, grinning.

FRED
Merry Christmas, Uncle!

SCROOGE
Bah. Humbug.

FRED
Christmas a humbug, Uncle? You don't mean that.

SCROOGE
If I could work my will, every idiot who goes about with "Merry Christmas" on his lips should be boiled with his own pudding.

Fred laughs, unoffended, and invites him to dinner. Scrooge refuses flatly. Fred exits, still cheerful. Two gentlemen enter seeking charity for the poor.

SCROOGE (CONT'D)
Are there no prisons? No workhouses?

GENTLEMAN
Many can't go there, and many would rather die.

SCROOGE
If they would rather die, they had better do it, and decrease the surplus population.

The gentlemen leave, disturbed. Scrooge locks up for the night.

CUT TO:

INT. SCROOGE'S CHAMBERS - NIGHT

Scrooge sits by a meager fire. The door-knocker downstairs seemed, for a moment, to wear Marley's face -- he dismisses it as bile.

A distant clanking. Chains dragging up the stairs.

The door swings open on its own. JACOB MARLEY'S GHOST enters -- transparent, wound in chains, cash-boxes, and padlocks.

SCROOGE
(terrified)
How now! What do you want with me?

MARLEY'S GHOST
Much! You will be haunted by Three Spirits.

SCROOGE
Couldn't I take 'em all at once, and have it over, Jacob?

MARLEY'S GHOST
Expect the first tomorrow, when the bell tolls one.

The ghost drifts to the window, moaning, and dissolves into a chorus of tormented spirits outside, all bound by chains of their own making.

DISSOLVE TO:

INT. SCROOGE'S CHAMBERS - NIGHT (LATER)

A bell tolls one. Light floods the room. The GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PAST appears -- childlike, flickering, strange.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PAST
Rise! And walk with me!

They pass through the wall itself.

CUT TO:

EXT. COUNTRY SCHOOL - DAY (MEMORY)

A young SCROOGE sits alone at a school desk, forgotten by his classmates over the holidays. Older Scrooge watches, his hardness cracking.

SCROOGE
(quietly)
I wish -- but it's too late now.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PAST
What is the matter?

SCROOGE
Nothing. There was a boy singing a carol at my door last night. I should like to have given him something, that's all.

CUT TO:

INT. FEZZIWIG'S WAREHOUSE - NIGHT (MEMORY)

A younger Scrooge, apprenticed, dances joyfully at a Christmas party thrown by old FEZZIWIG. Fiddles, laughter, warmth.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PAST
A small matter, to make these silly folks so full of gratitude.

SCROOGE
Small! He has the power to render us happy or unhappy -- to make our service light or burdensome.

He looks at his present self, ashamed.

SCROOGE (CONT'D)
I should like to be able to say a word or two to my clerk just now.

The scene shifts -- BELLE, a young woman, releases young Scrooge from their engagement, tears in her eyes, as she watches him choose gain over her.

BELLE
Another idol has displaced me -- a golden one.

Older Scrooge turns away, unable to watch.

SCROOGE
Spirit! Show me no more! Remove me from this place!

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

INT. SCROOGE'S CHAMBERS - NIGHT

The room transformed -- holly, turkeys, a roaring fire. The GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT, a jovial giant crowned with icicles and holly, reclines on a throne of food.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
Come in! Come in and know me better, man!

CUT TO:

INT. CRATCHIT HOME - NIGHT (VISION)

A small, poor, joyful house. Mrs. Cratchit and the children prepare a modest goose. BOB CRATCHIT enters carrying TINY TIM, his crippled son, on his shoulder, a small crutch in hand.

BOB CRATCHIT
(cheerful)
And how did little Tim behave?

TINY TIM (O.S.)
(from his father's shoulder)
He hoped the people saw him in church, because he was a cripple, and it might be pleasant for them to remember, upon Christmas Day, who made lame beggars walk and blind men see.

Scrooge watches, unseen, deeply moved.

SCROOGE
Spirit, tell me if Tiny Tim will live.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
I see a vacant seat, in the poor chimney corner, and a crutch without an owner, carefully preserved. If these shadows remain unaltered, the child will die.

SCROOGE
No, no! Say he will be spared!

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
(coldly, echoing Scrooge's own words)
If he be like to die, he had better do it, and decrease the surplus population.

Scrooge lowers his head, stricken with shame.

The Ghost opens his robe to reveal two wretched children clinging beneath it -- IGNORANCE and WANT.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT (CONT'D)
Beware them both, but most of all beware this boy, for on his brow I see that written which is Doom.

The Ghost and the vision dissolve into darkness.

CUT TO:

EXT. GRAVEYARD - NIGHT

A dark, silent figure -- the GHOST OF CHRISTMAS YET TO COME -- draped entirely in black, points a single hand toward a neglected headstone.

SCROOGE
(trembling)
Before I draw nearer to that stone, answer me one question. Are these the shadows of things that WILL be, or are they shadows of things that MAY be, only?

The Spirit doesn't answer. Scrooge approaches the grave, wipes away frost, and reads his own name.

SCROOGE (CONT'D)
(falling to his knees)
No, Spirit! Oh no, no! Hear me! I am not the man I was. Why show me this if I am past all hope?

He clutches at the Spirit's robe.

SCROOGE (CONT'D)
I will honor Christmas in my heart, and try to keep it all the year. I will live in the Past, the Present, and the Future. The Spirits of all Three shall strive within me. Oh, tell me I may sponge away the writing on this stone!

The black-robed figure shrinks, collapses, and dissolves into --

CUT TO:

INT. SCROOGE'S CHAMBERS - MORNING

-- the bedpost, which Scrooge is now clutching with both hands. Bright morning light. Bells ringing outside. Scrooge, still in his nightshirt, laughs -- a real, unfamiliar laugh.

SCROOGE
I am as light as a feather, I am as happy as an angel, I am as merry as a schoolboy!

He flings open the window and calls down to a boy in the street below.

SCROOGE (CONT'D)
What's today, my fine fellow?

BOY (O.S.)
Today? Why, CHRISTMAS DAY!

SCROOGE
I haven't missed it! Go and buy the prize turkey -- the big one! -- and take it to Bob Cratchit's, in Camden Town!

CUT TO:

INT. SCROOGE & MARLEY'S COUNTING-HOUSE - THE NEXT DAY

Bob Cratchit arrives late, flustered, expecting a scolding. Scrooge, feigning gruffness, rises from his desk.

SCROOGE
(mock-stern)
What do you mean by coming here at this time of day?

BOB CRATCHIT
I am very sorry, sir. It's only once a year, sir --

SCROOGE
(breaking into a grin)
I am not going to stand this sort of thing any longer -- and therefore I am about to raise your salary!

Bob stares, stunned.

SCROOGE (CONT'D)
A merry Christmas, Bob! A merrier Christmas than I've given you for many a year. I'll raise your salary and endeavor to assist your struggling family, and we will discuss your affairs this very afternoon over a bowl of smoking bishop.

Bob, speechless, can only nod as Scrooge claps him on the shoulder.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And it was always said of him that he knew how to keep Christmas well, if any man alive possessed the knowledge. And so, as Tiny Tim observed --

TINY TIM (V.O.)
God bless us, every one!

FADE OUT.

> THE END <
